chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Environmental protection and economic growth should be treated as linked goals: protect the natural systems that keep people healthy while keeping the economy competitive and reliable for workers and businesses. Set firm, science-based limits on pollution with clear timelines, flexible compliance options, and streamlined permitting for projects that measurably cut emissions and waste. Pair these standards with targeted transition help—training, wage support, and assistance for small firms and affected regions—so communities can adapt and share in the gains.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Environmental protection and economic growth should be pursued together by treating clean air, water, and land as essential to long-term prosperity and public health. Set clear, enforceable, science-based standards with predictable, phased timelines so businesses and skilled trades can plan and invest. Pair these rules with market incentives and targeted public investment in cleaner technology, along with funded retraining and support for workers and small businesses in transition. Ground decisions in local input and measurable outcomes so costs and benefits are shared fairly and communities see durable jobs and healthier resources.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Protecting clean air and water should go hand in hand with keeping the economy strong, because healthy communities and reliable jobs depend on each other. Set clear, science-based standards with predictable, phased timelines so businesses—especially small employers and skilled trades—can plan, comply, and keep people working. Pair those rules with market-based incentives and investments in cleaner domestic energy and manufacturing, plus job training and transition support for workers and communities most affected. Focus on measurable results, local input, and fair enforcement so stewardship strengthens prosperity rather than dividing it.
